C#
->2002 – C# 13 version
->It is an object-oriented programming language created by Microsoft that runs on the .NET Framework
C# is used for:
Mobile applications
Desktop applications
Web applications
Web services
Web sites
Games
VR
Database applications
Why Use C#?
It is one of the most popular programming languages in the world
It is easy to learn and simple to use
It has huge community support
C# is an object-oriented language which gives a clear structure to programs and allows code to be reused, lowering development costs
As C# is close to C, C++ and Java, it makes it easy for programmers to switch to C# or vice versa



Data Type

1-Integer data Type
Length find:- MinValue and MaxValue
Console.WriteLine(sbyte.MinValue + " to " + sbyte.MaxValue);
Console.WriteLine(byte.MinValue + " to " + byte.MaxValue);
Console.WriteLine(short.MinValue + " to " + short.MaxValue);
Console.WriteLine(ushort.MinValue + " to " + ushort.MaxValue);
Console.WriteLine(int.MinValue + " to " + int.MaxValue);
Console.WriteLine(uint.MinValue + " to " + uint.MaxValue);
Console.WriteLine(long.MinValue + " to " + long.MaxValue);
Console.WriteLine(ulong.MinValue + " to " + ulong.MaxValue);
Console.WriteLine(char.MinValue + " to " + char.MaxValue);

2-Boolean
using System;
using System.Linq;

public class HelloWorld
{
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
     int a=10;
     int b=5;
     int c=a>b; // add bool c=a>b then no error
     Console.WriteLine(a);

    }
}
//error- Cannot implicitly convert type 'bool' to 'int'

3-Float , Decimal and Double 

M==m and F==f , double me d likhna jaruri nhi h;
    float a=43.5342454F;    //7 range
    double b=3.56789064234567;    //15-16
    decimal d=345.323424M;       //28-29
    Console.WriteLine(d);

4-String and Character
 string b="bababa";
     char a='A';
     char c="A";  //error
     Console.WriteLine(b);
      Console.WriteLine(a);
     Console.WriteLine(c);
Console.ReadLine();

Escape Sequence-> 
string b="\"bababa ninja\"”; //   o/p-  "bababa ninja"
      Console.WriteLine(b);
string a="\\bababa ninja\\”;
      Console.WriteLine(a);  // o/p- \bababa ninja\
   
Verbatim Literal
—->  string s="D:\\deepanshu\\tiwari";
       Console.WriteLine(s);   / /D:\deepanshu\tiwari

—--> string s="D:\deepanshu\tiwari";
       Console.WriteLine(s);  // Error - Unrecognized escape sequence

To hum log @ ka use kare ge

—--> string s=@"D:\deepanshu\tiwari";
       Console.WriteLine(s);   // D:\deepanshu\tiwari


—-->  string s=@"D:\\deepanshu\\tiwari";
       Console.WriteLine(s);  // D:\\deepanshu\\tiwari


Data Type Conversion

Two Types :- 
1- Implicit
2-Explicit

Implicit - automatic Conversion by compiler
 int a=10;
 float b=a;
 Console.WriteLine(b);

Explicit 
Float a=10.2352f;
Int b=a;
Console.WriteLine(b); // error

Method 1 :-(int)
          Float a=10.2352f;
          Int b=(int)a;
          Console.WriteLine(b); // 10

Method 2:-
         float b=10.2345f;
         int a=Convert.ToInt32(b);
        Console.WriteLine(a);    //10
Eg:-
  string a="10";
   string b="10";
   int c=a+b;
   Console.WriteLine(c) //error


 string a="10";
 string b="10";
 int c=Convert.ToInt32(a)+Convert.ToInt32(b);
 Console.WriteLine(c);   //20


Method 3:- int.Parse(only int string leta h agar float denge to error)

 string a="10";
   string b="10";
   int c=int.Parse(a)+int.Parse(b);
   Console.WriteLine(c); //20

  string a="10.5";
   string b="10";
   int c=int.Parse(a)+int.Parse(b);
   Console.WriteLine(c);//error

string a="10.5";
   string b="10";
   float c=float.Parse(a)+float.Parse(b);  // agar int c me store kare ge to error dega
   Console.WriteLine(c); //20.5

UserInput :-
  Console.WriteLine("Enter first number :");
  float f1=Console.ReadLine(); //error-Cannot implicitly convert type 'string' to 'float'  or   yaha pe float likho ya int error dega to hame explicit conversion karna pade ga   .       String me nhi dega error 

Only String leta h -> to float.Parse(),Conver.ToFloat32 use kare ge     (int) wala error dega to yeh use nhi kare ge

  Console.WriteLine("Enter first number :");
  float f1=float.Parse(Console.ReadLine()); //10.234

